{ First, we start with d4. } { [%csl Bd4][%cal Bd2d4] }
1. d4 d5 { Now, we play Nf3 } { [%csl Bf3][%cal Bg1f3] } 2. Nf3 (2. Bf4 { This is covered in section 5. }) 2... Nf6 { We'll now play Bf4 } { [%csl Bf4][%cal Bc1f4] } 3. Bf4 { This piece placement let's black recognize that we are playing the London System. } { [%csl Bf3,Bf4,Bd4] } 3... c5 { Support the pawn with e3 } { [%csl Be3][%cal Be2e3] } 4. e3 Nc6 { Support that pawn even further with c3 } { [%csl Bc3][%cal Bc2c3] } 5. c3 { This is what we call the Pawn Pyramid. The pawn pyramid is like this pawn structure. We usually do this only if they play c5. } { [%csl Bc3,Bd4,Be3,Bb2,Bf2][%cal Bf2e3,Be3d4,Bb2c3,Bc3d4] } 5... e6 { We now place the knight on d2 } { [%csl Bd2][%cal Bb1d2] } 6. Nbd2 Bd6 { Always meet Bd6 with Bg3 } { [%csl Bg3][%cal Bf4g3] } 7. Bg3 O-O { Finally, we complete the system with Bd3 } { [%csl Bd3][%cal Bf1d3] } 8. Bd3 Re8 { Now, this is our middlegame plan: Play Ne5 followed by f4 and reroute the bishop to h4 to give space for our pieces to attack. We need to keep our light-squared bishop because it is very important in the attack. } 9. Ne5! { We'll just play f4, castle the king, and play Bh4 to give room for the rook to swing over the f3 followed by going to g3 or f3. We also give space for the queen to join the party.
--Point--
You want to create a kingside attack and just destroy them on that side of the board. } { [%csl Gg1,Be5][%cal Ge1g1,Rf4e5,Rd4e5,Yf2f4] } *


