{ We play d4. } { [%csl Bd4][%cal Bd2d4] }
1. d4 Nf6 { Now we play Bf4. } { [%csl Bf4][%cal Bc1f4] } 2. Bf4 e6 { Now we develop the knight to f3. } { [%csl Bf3][%cal Bg1f3] } (2... d5 3. e3) 3. Nf3 (3. e3 { This transposes. Play Nf3 instead to continue. }) 3... b6 { This is the QID Setup. We respond with e3. } { [%csl Be3][%cal Be2e3] } 4. e3 Bb7 { We now play Nbd2. } { [%csl Bd2][%cal Bb1d2] } 5. Nbd2 (5. Bd3 { This transposes. Play Nbd2 instead to continue. }) (5. Be2 { Playable, but not recommended because you want the bishop on d3. If there is a pawn on g6, place the bishop here, but if there is no pawn there, then why not play Bd3 instead? }) (5. h3 { This transposes. Play Nbd2 instead to continue. }) (5. c3 { This transposes. Play Nbd2 instead to continue. }) (5. Nc3 { You block the c-pawn! } { [%csl Rc3][%cal Rc2c3] }) (5. a4 { Playable, but I recommend that you complete the system first then play this move of a4. }) (5. c4 { This isn't the London System anymore. }) 5... c5 { We respond with c3. } { [%csl Bc3][%cal Bc2c3] } 6. c3 { We have now created the pawn pyramid. } (6. Bd3 { This is playable, but supporting the center is better (this transposes though). }) (6. h3 { This is playable, but supporting the center is better (it is preferable to play h3 only if the g5 square is covered by their pieces). }) 6... Be7 { Since they are indirectly covering the g5 square adequately, we now play h3 to give our bishop some room to move away if ever Nh5 would be played. } { [%csl Bh3][%cal Bh2h3] } 7. h3 (7. Bd3?! { They play Nh5 and win the bishop pair. } { [%csl Bh5][%cal Bf6h5] }) (7. Be2?! { They play Nh5 and win the bishop pair. } { [%csl Bh5][%cal Bf6h5] }) 7... O-O { Now we can safely develop the bishop to d3. } { [%csl Bd3][%cal Bf1d3] } 8. Bd3 d6 { We now castle. } { [%csl Bg1][%cal Be1g1] } 9. O-O Nbd7 { We place the rook on e1. } { [%csl Be1][%cal Bf1e1] } 10. Re1 Re8 { We now play e4! } { [%csl Be4][%cal Be3e4] } 11. e4! { We strike in the center immediately! } 11... Bf8 { [%csl Be5][%cal Be4e5] } 12. e5! { We are now better here! Almost +2.0! You have a strong kingside attack going on and you will surely win this game.
--Point--
You want to create a kingside attack with means of e4 followed by e5. Greek Gift Sacrifices are best once the knight moves. } *


