[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ We play d4. } { [%csl Bd4][%cal Bd2d4] }
1. d4 Nf6 { We place the bishop on f4. } { [%csl Bf4][%cal Bc1f4] } 2. Bf4 c5 { Now, we push the pawn to e3. } { [%csl Ge3][%cal Ge2e3] } 3. e3 (3. d5 { I will talk about this move in a separate chapter. } 3... Qb6 4. Na3 Qxb2) (3. dxc5 { I will talk about this move in a separate chapter. }) (3. c3? { They can play Qb6 and we are worse. } { [%csl Rb2][%cal Rd8b6,Rb6b2] }) 3... Qb6 { This is an important move to remember: Na3! } { [%csl Ba3][%cal Bb1a3] } 4. Na3! { This is what I recommend as it limits black's options! This is a small deviation but we need to do what needs to be done. } (4. Nc3 { Black has lots of options but I will cover this in a separate chapter. }) (4. b3 { You create too many dark-squared weaknesses on the queenside. Not good at all. } { [%csl Ra3,Rb2,Rc3] }) 4... Qxb2 { We now play Nb5! } { [%csl Bb5][%cal Ba3b5] } 5. Nb5! { We are threatening to fork on c7!
If Na6 is played, then you play a3 followed by Rb1 and Rb3 which just traps the queen after Ne2 and Nc1 or you could play Bc4 Rb4 and win the queen that way. } 5... Nd5 { Can you find a forced repetition? } 6. Rb1 { Yes, that is the move! } (6. a3 { This is a decent line.
Play Rb1 to continue. } 6... a5 (6... a6 7. Rb1 Qa2 8. Qc1 axb5 9. Ra1 Qxa1 10. Qxa1) 7. Rb1 Qa2 8. Qc1) 6... Qxa2 { I hope you know what to play now to force a draw. } { [%csl Ba1][%cal Bb1a1] } 7. Ra1 Qb2 { [%csl Bb1][%cal Ba1b1] } 8. Rb1 Qa2 { [%csl Ba1][%cal Bb1a1] } 9. Ra1 Qb2 { [%csl Bb1][%cal Ba1b1] } 10. Rb1 Qa2 $10 { the game has officially been drawn =.
--Point--
You can either opt for a draw with 6. Rb1, or you could play 6. a3, and that leads into a forced line (6. a3 a6 7. Rb1 Qa2 8. Qc1 axb5 9. Ra1 Qxa1 10. Rxa1) where you win the queen but in exchange for a couple of pieces (rook & knight). } *


