1... Bd6 { Pattern #2: Meet Bd6 with Bg3 } 2. Bg3! { If they ever take our bishop, we take with the h-pawn and open up the h-file and also maybe no one might tell you this, but if they exchanged on g3, we are strategically and positionally winning. You may ask "Why is it strategically and positionally winning?" It is because that they exchanged their good bishop for our bad bishop, and that means they have the bad light-squared bishop while our light-squared bishop is a good bishop. It is strategically winning because they just helped us open up the h-file for no reason. That is why they shouldn't take on g3. } 2... O-O { We play Bd3 and just continue the system. } 3. Bd3 { We have pressure on the long diagonal and now we play chess. Let's move on to the next pattern.
--Point--
You want to provoke them to take and if so, you recapture with the h-pawn and open up your rook on h1. } *


