{ Start with d4 } { [%csl Bd4][%cal Bd2d4] }
1. d4 d5 { Play Nf3 } { [%csl Bf3][%cal Bg1f3] } 2. Nf3 Nf6 { Play Bf4 } { [%csl Rf4][%cal Rc1f4] } 3. Bf4 c5 { Play e3 } { [%csl Ye3][%cal Ye2e3] } 4. e3 Nc6 { Support the pawn with c3 } { [%csl Yc3][%cal Yc2c3] } 5. c3 Bg4 { Play Nbd2 } { [%csl Rd2][%cal Rb1d2] } 6. Nbd2 e6 { This is where the trap starts. We play Bb5 } { [%csl Bb5][%cal Bf1b5] } 7. Bb5 Bd6 { Now, we play Qa4 } { [%csl Ba4][%cal Bd1a4] } 8. Qa4 O-O { Take the knight on c6 } { [%csl Bc6][%cal Bb5c6] } 9. Bxc6 bxc6 { Take the bishop on d6 } { [%csl Rd6][%cal Rf4d6] } 10. Bxd6 Qxd6 { And now you set up the trap. Play Ne5 } { [%csl Ye5][%cal Yf3e5] } 11. Ne5 { Their most natural move is actually a blunder. } 11... Rfc8?? { This is now a big blunder because we can take the bishop on g4 followed by play dxc5! } { [%csl Bg4,Yc5][%cal Be5g4,Yd4c5,Ra4g4] } 12. Nxg4! Nxg4 { We now play dxc5 } { [%csl Bc5,Rg4][%cal Bd4c5,Ra4g4] } 13. dxc5 Qxc5 { And now we take the knight with our queen } { [%csl Gg4][%cal Ga4g4] } 14. Qxg4 { GG! } { [%csl Bd2] } *


