{ [%csl Gd4][%cal Gd2d4] }
1. d4 Nf6 { Develop the bishop to f4 } { [%csl Bf4][%cal Bc1f4] } 2. Bf4 e6 { Play Nf3 } { [%csl Bf3][%cal Bg1f3] } 3. Nf3 c5 { Play e3 } { [%csl Re3][%cal Re2e3] } 4. e3 b6 { Place the knight on d2 } { [%csl Yd2][%cal Yb1d2] } 5. Nbd2 Bb7 { We now set up a trap. We play Nc4 } { [%csl Rc4][%cal Rd2c4] } 6. Nc4!? { This is a very provoking move because it just provokes black to play d5 or d6 THINKING that our threat is Nd6+. But that is not our threat. If they play d6, we take on c5. Once we take on c5, they could take by b-pawn or d-pawn. If they take by d-pawn, we exchange the queens and play Ng5 and once they defend with Ke8, we just play Ne5. If they take by b-pawn, we just take the pawn on d6 and we are winning. } 6... d5 { We now play Nce5 } { [%csl Be5][%cal Bc4e5] } 7. Nce5! { We target f7! } { [%csl Rf7][%cal Re5f7] } 7... Nbd7 { We now play Bb5! } { [%csl Bb5][%cal Bf1b5] } 8. Bb5 a6 { Just play Ng5 } { [%csl Rf7][%cal Rf3g5,Rg5f7,Re5f7] } 9. Ng5 { [%csl Rf7][%cal Re5f7,Rg5f7] } 9... axb5 { Play Nexf7 } { [%csl Rf7][%cal Re5f7] } 10. Nexf7 Qe7 { Take the rook on h8 } { [%csl Yh8][%cal Yf7h8] } 11. Nxh8 h6 { You just play Ng6 } { [%csl Rg6][%cal Rh8g6] } 12. Ng6 { GG! } *


