{ [%csl Bd4][%cal Bd2d4] }
1. d4 Nf6 { [%csl Bf4][%cal Bc1f4] } 2. Bf4 g6 { Now, let us tackle the alternatives. Let us play e3. } 3. e3 (3. c4 Bg7 4. Nc3 O-O 5. e4) 3... Bg7 { [%csl Bf3][%cal Bg1f3] } 4. Nf3 d6 { Against d6, you need to play h3. } { [%csl Bh3][%cal Bh2h3] } 5. h3 O-O { Where does the bishop go? } { [%csl Gd3,Ge2][%cal Gf1e2,Gf1d3] } 6. Be2! { Just like I told you in section 1, place the bishop on e2 against the kingside fianchetto structures.
The bishop is more active on this square and unlike it being on d3, it isn't biting on stone because it is on e2. } (6. Bd3 { The bishop is just staring at stone and it shouldn't be here. } { [%csl Rh7,Rg6][%cal Rd3h7] }) (6. Bc4 { This is not a London System. }) (6. c3 { Engine recommends this, but it is too early! }) (6. Nbd2 { You are developing this knight too soon. }) (6. Bh2 { There is no need to retreat the bishop. There is no sign that they will play e5 and attack our bishop. }) (6. Bg3 { There is no need to retreat the bishop. There is no sign that they will play e5 and attack our bishop. }) (6. Nc3 { Playable, but not the best move. }) 6... Nbd7 { [%csl Bh1][%cal Be1h1] } 7. O-O b6 { [%csl Ba4][%cal Ba2a4] } 8. a4 { This is a common pattern when they play b6 and we want to play a5 and place that pawn on a6. } 8... a6 { [%csl Bc3][%cal Bc2c3] } 9. c3 { We have now built the triangle (pyramid).
We do not need to play c4 and weaken the b4 square. } { [%csl Gc3,Gd4,Ge3] } 9... Bb7 { [%csl Bd2][%cal Bb1d2] } 10. Nbd2 c5 { [%csl Bh2][%cal Bf4h2] } 11. Bh2 { This is a move in anticipation on e5. } 11... Qc7 { [%csl Bb3][%cal Bd1b3] } 12. Qb3 { White has a good position here. Your main plan is to play Re1, Bd3 or Bf1, and you want to play e4 at some point and if you are able to do that, you will be better.
--Point--
You want to get a solid structure before striking in the center on e4. You want to play a more positional approach to this and slowly but surely get a better position and convert it into a win. } { [%csl Re4,Yd3][%cal Ye2f1,Bf1e1,Re3e4,Ye2d3] } *


