{ [%csl Bd4][%cal Bd2d4] }
1. d4 Nf6 { [%csl Bf4][%cal Bc1f4] } 2. Bf4 g6 { There is another alternative to e3 and Nc3. We can also play Nd2 } { [%csl Bd2][%cal Bb1d2] } 3. Nd2 { The idea is to play e4! } 3... Bg7 { [%csl Be4][%cal Be2e4] } 4. e4 d6 { [%csl Bf3][%cal Bg1f3] } 5. Ngf3 O-O { [%csl Bc3][%cal Bc2c3] } 6. c3 { We have a normal London System but the pawn is on e4 which is more aggressive and more advantageous. } 6... Nbd7 { [%csl Ge2][%cal Gf1e2] } 7. Be2 Re8 { [%csl Bh3][%cal Bh2h3] } 8. h3 { We now have a square for the bishop. } 8... e5 { [%csl Be5][%cal Bd4e5] } 9. dxe5 dxe5 { [%csl Be3][%cal Bf4e3] } 10. Be3 { We move the bishop here as it is more active. } 10... b6 { [%csl Bc2][%cal Bd1c2] } 11. Qc2 Bb7 { [%csl Bg1][%cal Be1g1] } 12. O-O Qe7 { [%csl Ba4][%cal Ba2a4] } 13. a4 a5 { If they ever played a6, we play a5 and once they play b5, we just play c4 and we are better. } { [%csl Bb4][%cal Bb2b4] } 14. b4 axb4 { [%csl Bb4][%cal Bc3b4] } 15. cxb4 Qxb4 16. Ng5 { We have a threat of Bc4, and we are soon going to use the open files on the queenside to gain an advantage. I recommend you analyze this with the engine but only do that once you have thought of your own ideas.
--Point--
You want to control the center, keep your king cozy on g1, do some stuff on the queenside and just pressure them. } 16... h6 17. Qxc7 Rab8 18. Nxf7 Kxf7 19. Nc4 Bf8 20. Rfd1 Bxe4 21. Rxd7+ Nxd7 22. Qxd7+ Re7 23. Qd6 Reb7 24. Qxe5 Re8 25. Qb5 Re6 26. Bg4 Qxb5 27. Bxe6+ Kxe6 28. axb5 Bd3 *


