[StudyName "Master the London System!"]
[ChapterName "Section 5: London vs d5 setups (2. Bf4 instead of 2. Nf3) 2... c5"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/K4oR74Te/jH2CTPGo"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/mAtteoYOsef07"]
[UTCDate "2026.05.27"]
[UTCTime "12:28:23"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ [%csl Bd4][%cal Bd2d4] }
1. d4 d5 { [%csl Bf4][%cal Bc1f4] } 2. Bf4 { By the way, this is known as the Accelerated London System. The normal London System usually starts with playing Nf3 first instead of Bf4 on move 2. This is what most London System players play (2. Bf4). } (2. Nf3 { We are studying the 2. Bf4 move order. } { [%csl Rf3,Gf4][%cal Rg1f3,Gc1f4] }) 2... c5 { I actually recommend playing something you wouldn't expect. Most players would play e3, but you might transpose into another different opening which usually occurs when you play e4 on the first move. } 3. dxc5!? { It seems like we are just giving up our center, but this has some venom lurking inside its body! } { [%csl Rc5][%cal Rd4c5] } (3. e3 { Playable, but transposes into the Exchange Caro-Kann after cxd4 exd4. }) 3... Nc6 { How can you strike in the center? } 4. e4! { You need to strike in the center! If d4 is ever played, just play c3 and you are better. If e6 is played, just take on d5 and play Nc3 } { [%csl Rd5,Re4][%cal Rd5e4,Re4d5] } (4. c4? { Extremely bad move. Black can play e5 and control the whole center. } { [%csl Ge5,Rd4,Rc4,Rf4,Re4][%cal Ge7e5,Re5d4,Re5f4,Rd5c4,Rd5e4] }) 4... dxe4 { I mean, why not take on d8? } 5. Qxd8+ Nxd8 { Ch... ch... check 'em king!! } 6. Bb5+ Nc6 { A... a... attack 'em pawns!! } { [%csl Bc3][%cal Bb1c3] } 7. Nc3 Nf6 { Why not c... castle? } { [%csl Bc1][%cal Be1c1] } 8. O-O-O { White has t... th.. the initiative and you are j.. just better here!
--Point--
You want to achieve an active position! } *


[Event "Master the London System!: Section 5: London vs Benoni (most aggressive alternative)"]
