{ This is the surprise that you were waiting for. If you can play the London System with white, that means I should tell you that you can play it with black. Black London is just the same as White London just with a tempo down and colours reversed. Easy right? }
1. Nf3 { [%csl Bf6][%cal Bg8f6] } 1... Nf6 2. g3 { [%csl Bd5][%cal Bd7d5] } 2... d5 { Easy isn't it? } 3. Bg2 { [%csl Bf5][%cal Bc8f5] } 3... Bf5 { This now resembles the London System but with the black pieces. } { [%csl Gf5,Gf6,Gd5] } 4. O-O { [%csl Be6][%cal Be7e6] } 4... e6 { Isn't this a London System? } 5. d3 { It surely is! } { [%csl Bh6][%cal Bh7h6] } 5... h6 6. Nbd2 { [%csl Be7][%cal Bf8e7] } 6... Be7 7. Qe1 { [%csl Bh7][%cal Bf5h7] } 7... Bh7 { We play this in anticipation of e4. } 8. e4 { [%csl Bg8][%cal Be8g8] } 8... O-O 9. Qe2 { [%csl Bc6][%cal Bc7c6] } 9... c6 { Pyramid has been created! } { [%csl Rf7,Re6,Rd5,Rc6,Rb7][%cal Gb7c6,Gc6d5,Gf7e6,Ge6d5] } 10. Re1 { [%csl Ba5][%cal Ba7a5] } 10... a5 { We want to expand on the queenside and create weaknesses.
--Point--
We play the London System with the black pieces (can only be played against the Reti Opening, Nimzo-Larsen Attack and Reversed Queen's Indian Defense). We usually put the dark-squared bishop on e7 and continue with our system. We want to weaken their dark-squares and win the game!
Hope you enjoyed this study but... not yet! There is still one more chapter and that is the end of the study! } *


